# What is Veneering

Veneering is a woodworking technique in which thin sheets of wood, known as veneer, are applied to a stable substrate.

The method allows furniture makers to use highly decorative wood species while maintaining structural stability. Instead of constructing an entire object from rare wood, a thin layer of veneer can be applied to a stable base material.

Veneering has been used in furniture making for centuries and became highly developed in European cabinetmaking traditions. It allowed craftspeople to create complex decorative surfaces while using wood efficiently.

Veneer can be arranged in patterns that emphasize the natural figure of wood, such as bookmatching, slip matching or radial arrangements. These patterns highlight the visual qualities of the material and often become an important part of furniture design.

Traditional veneering techniques frequently use hot hide glue and specialized tools to press the veneer onto the surface. These methods allow the veneer to bond securely while remaining compatible with traditional woodworking practices.

Understanding veneering is an important part of cabinetmaking because it connects material knowledge, craftsmanship and furniture design.

At Bensari Workshop traditional veneering techniques are explored as part of a broader understanding of woodworking and furniture construction.
